segments.text: Did you have any favorite teachers when you were at A&M?
Oh, I remember some of them.
Which ones can you remember?
Well, I didn't have any favorites among the chemistry department, because the biggest percentage of them busted chemistry.
I remember I went and talked to Dr. Brazell about it.
I said, now, Dr. Brazell, I'm no top A student, but I says, I can name you some students here who never busted a course till they got in the chemistry department.
But we had a lot of friends.
It was good cooperation between the faculty and the students.
As a overall, you would say you found the faculty pretty helpful to you then?
Oh yeah, they were, they were, they were swell fellows.
We liked them all.
Well, I said we'd do it.
I guess the chemistry professor was all right, but their department wasn't very much in favor.
Earlier today when we were at lunch, you mentioned a couple of faculty members.
I think you mentioned Dr. Francis.
Dr. Francis was head of the veterinary department.
But you didn't have any classes under him?
Yes, I had classes under him, yes.
Well, I was wondering, since you were in agronomy, according to the 17th.
Yes, but the agronomy course did have a course in two veterinary courses in the agronomy.
Dr. Marsteller, he was also in the veterinary.
He was head of that school for a while.
He succeeded Dr. Francis.
Okay.
What did the students overall think about the administration?
And I guess maybe I better make a dual role of administration because you had the president who ran the academic side and you had the commandant who kind of controlled the military.
Known as the bull.
The bull, right.
Did the students feel favorably towards both of those people or?
Oh, I think so.
Of course, they kind of feared the military because they were always so strong about discipline.
Then what about Dr. Bazell?
You mentioned earlier that you talked to him about the chemistry.
He was very, very fine, very well liked, very popular among the boys.
Everybody liked him.
He knew a lot of them by name.
I knew him very intimately.
Ms. Brazell used to entertain some of my dance dates.
Girls would come down and I was in his home a good many times.
I believe something I read indicated he taught a Sunday school class for a good long while while he was president.
I expect he did.
He was a very consecrated Christian gentleman.
Can you think of any new traditions which were started while you were a student?

I know the bonfire precedes you and several other things which were still being done today were being done before you came, but one of the things that's very hard for us to pin down is when did something start?
Can you think of anything that was started during the four years you were there?
I don't recall.
Some of the gills that the student body used today were started during my
Saw the Texas Longhorns on.
Saw the Varsity Horns on.
Saw the Varsity Horns on the starter.
Chickaroo rim, Chickaroo rim.
Rough, tough, still rough Texas A&M.
That was one of the starters there.
I think they still use them.
I believe so, yes.
Freshman, everybody went to the ball games.
If you didn't play, just especially freshman.
He didn't go to the athletic events.
He just got his butt patted.
Did now, of course, they stand during the ball game.
Did you stand then or did you sit down?
Yeah, that was the 12th man.
Yeah, they'd stand.
I think the spirit was, I don't know anything about the spirit, the core spirit, now.
I would believe it would be better then than it is now.
Well then it was somewhat of a unanimous thing and now it's an optional.
That's right.
It was very unpatriotic not to be that.
I remember a couple of years after I graduated, to give you an example of how the Corps thought,
I drove in, me and my wife drove into the campus about 11 o'clock one morning, Thanksgiving morning, for the Thanksgiving game against the university.
And I stopped my car at the gate and I saw a freshman standing off to one side over there and I said, wait, I believe I'll see how the game's coming out.
Well, I said, what does he know about it?
I said, well, I just want to talk to one of these freshmen.
So I went over there and I said,
young man, how's the game coming out?
Well, he looked kind of far off.
I said, well, I just finished it two or three years ago, and if I knew how you boys felt about this game today, I'd know how it was coming out.
And the kid was teed up.
He come in, he's crying, standing there by himself.
He says, we're going to beat those SOBs just to show as we play this afternoon.
He said, I haven't slept on the campus for three nights.
He said, they run me out every night.
I said, we're going to win.
So I got back to the car.
I told my wife, I said, well, we're going to win the ball game.
She said, is he a prophet?
I said, no, I just got the feeling of the Corps.
And they used to win then.
And you can check it, but I think
14, 15, and 16 that our football team wasn't scored on.
You can check that and see.
I don't want you to go.
Well, let's see.
I believe something we talked about earlier, the branding of the university steer.
I believe the university's intention to brand it with the 16 score

uh would have indicated we were scored on in 16. maybe so i don't know what he is i have a list of the scores but uh while we're talking about that branding of the steer since since uh that branding was done during 17 when when you were a senior what can you tell us about that incident
Before I set in on the planning of it, I wasn't among the five that went over there.
You have in the annual who went.
The branding team, they called it.
And I set in on the planning of it and what we were going to do.
And I saw them that night when they got back.
They said the job had been done.
What prompted them to go ahead and brand the steer?
Well, Lutcher Stark, who's a very wealthy
man, a university alumnus.
He gave the university, he was an alumnus down in Beaumont area, Fort Arthur area.
He gave them a very beautiful steel.
It was orange and white steel with long horns.
And so he was, I guess you'd call him the mascot.
And between halves,
Two university cowboys would have their steer on rope, bring them out, and circle them around.
So they were supposed to beat us that year, but we did win 13 to nothing.
I don't know whose idea it was.
I think it was a very good one.
Somebody decided to just go in and brand that darn steer.
But our score went up.
And he never did appear in public after that.
I understood that they gave him to one of the charity institutions over in Austin, butchered him.
Made beef out of him.

We have a clipping in the archives that indicated that they butchered him and had a banquet at which representatives from both schools were invited and they supposedly divided the hide between the two schools.
I didn't hear that.
But we can't...
prove that.
There was a clipping and it's pasted on the back of one of the pictures we have of the branded steer.
A student by the name of Atkinson, he was kind of an amateur photographer around there.
He went over there with them and took a picture of the steer.
And so they took his camera away from him over there on the scene, but he was sharp enough
to admit it, as soon as he snapped the steer, he took the film out of his car, out of his camera, and put them in his pocket.
And the university boys rushed down there on him and caused quite a bit of fight.
And they took this boy's camera and broke it up on the pavement.
But he had the film in his pocket.
So he came back and made an enlargement of it, eight and a half by 11 or something of the steer.
Sold them at 25 cents a piece, and I think everybody down there bought them.
Well, I've seen several.
He probably made out pretty well on them.
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, he charged them too much a piece.
That was the most popular picture around there, I'm sure, except another one that he sold, that picture of September Morn, the girl in the water.
We talked earlier at lunch today about the taking of the rice owl which occurred I think during the same school year, didn't I?
I believe it was the same school year.
Do you have any recollections about that episode?
Yes.
Rice had this owl.
As I remember it, it must have been five feet tall, a stuffed owl.
So the boys stole it and brought it back up and put it in the armory and locked the door.
Where was the armory then?
I think it was a room in the old main building, if I remember right.
It probably would have been the new main building.
The old one burned.
Yeah, well, it was the one that's still there now.
So, naturally, the rice men wanted to get the owl back.
So they employed a man from the Burns Detective Agency to come up there and locate it.
They had been up there and tried to find it, and they couldn't find it.
So they employed this guy, and so he came up there and located it.
So then he phoned and the rice men came up there and they got in there about 11 o'clock at night and broke in the army and started back with it.
And they captured this guy, this Burns Detective Agency.
And they had a kangaroo court up on the old Ross Hotel that was there.
And they were very much
rode up over that bird and he came up there for a fee.
Said if it had been sportsmanship or rice boys, well that's all right.
But that guy was hired to come up there.
So they threatened every way to kill him from that on down.
So finally up there on the second floor of Ross Hall, we had him up in the room.
And they decided to cut his hair.
And they made him bald-headed with some clippers.
I remember that just as well as what happened yesterday.
And a plane coming out of Bryan going south.
It was about 1 o'clock or 1.30 or something.
They had just got through clipping him.
And they asked him if he thought he could catch that train.
And he said he believed he could.
He was scared.
I thought they were going to hurt him.
So they opened the door, and he hit the sidewalk rock.
And he caught the train and went to Houston.
Did the boy that took the owl get away?
Was that any problems?
They got it back to Houston some way.
They scattered out.
They took it back in the automobile.
And a bunch of fellows got on this one o'clock train and stopped off at every station between College Station and Houston.
I don't believe they found it.
I think they got back to Houston, if I remember right.
Something else has occurred to me to back up a minute about this university mascot.
This one that was branded, was that the first one they ever had?
Yeah, that was the first longhorn steer they had.
Beautiful animal.
Well, I had understood that it was a magnificent animal.
They named him Bevo because that was a
Back in Prohibition days, that was a near beer, you know.
Non-intoxicating drink that had a beer flavor, I believe it was.
Yeah.
Was that name given to him before he was branded, do you know?
I don't know.
That's one of those things.
One of the things we've been trying to track down is one story that has been handed down was that the boys over at the University in Austin took that 13-0 and branded over it and made Bevo out of it.
I don't know.
and from the pictures I've seen with, it would have to be some very strange looking letters too.
Well they didn't, he never did come out anymore.
He lost his soldier's mandate.
That's the idea after he got that offer.
Yeah, well I think that
some more on the barbecue.
I believe that it was in January of 1920 that they finally butchered him and had a barbecue.
That was after the war, you see.
And we have on file an invitation to that barbecue in the gymnasium over at... That's interesting.
...in Austin.
See, I left the door.
Reveille, the dog.
That was during my day, the first reveille.
Well, we have a file.
I'm sure you do have a big file.
Newspaper clippings and so forth and pictures.
And somewhere on campus we have a painting of the first reveille.
Well, the first reveille was during my term.
And then, of course, we have files on the successors as well, the second and third reveilles.
And then we had some files of some other dogs.
I guess at one time or another there were efforts to, between the first and the second Reveille, to have other dogs as mascots, but it never seemed to work out.
Do they still have a Reveille?
Yeah, still have a Reveille.
And still under the charge of e-company.
Were there any girls in any of the classes that you attended when you were there?
The reason I ask is that all the professors' daughters tried to get in on some courses, but they couldn't.
The professors lived on the campus.
Well, I had understood from some people that, and I believe one of them was C.W.
Crawford in mechanical engineering, that from time to time there were a few who
Took some courses, and I believe his sister- Was that prior to World War I?
I'm not sure that it was.
I think it was after World War I.
Because his sister, I believe, finished a degree there in 24, which means she would have started after the war, probably.
Of course, there were the Hudson twins, much, much earlier than that, who took some courses in engineering.
And they, I guess, finished the whole curriculum, but didn't get a degree.
We know that a lot of the students who were at A&M had jobs of one sort or another to help make ends meet or help pay their tuition.
Did you ever have a job when you were there?
No, I didn't.
Okay.
Did you know people who did?
Oh, yeah.
There's a lot of boys who worked with me.
What sort of things did they do?
Well, all the way from dice shooting on down.
I know a boy went through that, I guess, four years, the last two or three years, with his dice.
But they had legitimate jobs.
They worked down in the barns.
They worked in the laboratories.
They did janitor work, not in the barracks.
They had men to do that, but in the classrooms.
That's why there was some job to work, down at the dairy.
different places.
Do you have any idea how much they were paid?
I have no idea.

Did the students who played, now this would be on the regular teams of football, baseball, basketball, and so forth, have better treatment say than the rest of you fellows who didn't participate in those?
Well they did
athletics table down in the mess hall.
They got, I expect they got more stakes than we did.
You had it once a week.
We had it on Thursday night, but they didn't have a, they weren't off in a barrack to themselves.
They were scattered throughout the Corps, and they were, they were relieved of a lot of military drilling.
they were working on out there, they were excused.
They were excused from walking the post.
I would imagine during the time that the rescue students were in your afternoon drills, why three days a week they'd be practicing football.
I noticed that from the Longhorn, the year that you graduated, getting your picture and your major and so forth and so on, indicated that you were a member of the Ross Volunteers.
How were you chosen to be in that group?
That was highly competitive.
It was limited to a certain number, and I don't know, I don't recall how many.
And you were voted on.
They'd have an election in the spring of the year, or the next fall, and they met on Sunday afternoon.
And each fella, he'd have his friend that he'd want to get into Ross Volunteers, and he'd put his name up for election.
So you had to be nominated by somebody.
Yes.
Your friend would put your name up and they would vote on it.
the one that have room for a certain number.
And of all the men that were nominated by their friends, the one that got the ones maybe that had 30 openings, whatever the opening was, the ones that got the most votes by then they were elected.
Very, very fair.
So who then voted?
All the people who were members of the Ross Volunteers?
Yeah, the Ross Volunteers would vote, you see.
I'd want Bill Jones, for example.
Another fella would want Sam Smith, put his name up, and then make a list, and they'd vote on it.
And then you'd vote for, if they needed 30, you'd pick out the 30 men that you wanted, and the other fella would pick out the 30 that he wanted, and the one that got the most votes would get in.
For whatever number they needed.
That's right.
They had that many vacancies.
Uh-huh.
Okay.
Did being in...
The Ross Volunteers were only juniors and seniors, right?
That's right.
Did that require a considerable more amount of drill than your regular three hours a week?
No, it didn't.
Not too much drill.
You'd get to wear a white uniform at the dance.
That was the way it was going on.
They'd wear a Ross Volunteer white uniform.
At the dances and other socials.
At any of the dances?
That's right.
Did you wear your white uniform or anything other than the social occasion?
No, that's all.
Just the social occasions.
You wore your regular uniform.
So it didn't excuse you from any other drill?
No, no.
You'd still be a member of your regular company?
That's right.
Is it that way now?
I believe it is.
How bad is it?
You still have to be in the Corps, first of all, to be in the Ross Volunteers.
Well, of course, everybody was in the Corps then.
Yeah.
And I believe that it's still juniors and seniors.
And I'm not sure whether it's- They lost their understanding when they didn't make it to Compulsory Corps.
I guess you have the record of it.
In World War I, I think that'll bear out investigation.
They furnished more officers than West Point.
I believe in World War II also.
Also World War II.
See, my class was a senior, and we were seniors there.
To graduate in June, they graduated us in April.
That is, they let us go on into service in April, and graduated us early to get into service.
Were there any academic requirements?
Did you have to have a certain grade or something to be in the Ross Volunteers?
Or no drill competence or anything like that?
I think there may be some of that now.
I'm not sure that they're still chosen by the other members.
I probably should check on that to see exactly what the procedures are.
But I believe...
Academic rating had nothing to do with it.
I believe you have to have a certain amount of academic rating.
I think it would probably be good if it was.
Let's go on.
You indicated that your class graduated early, and I gather 100% of them went into the service immediately.
Oh, yes.
Everyone that could stand a physical examination went in.
And where did you, where did you report to then?
Most of us reported, well different places.
Some of them went in, most of them though reported to Camp Leon Springs in San Antonio.
And then of course the others, they went to the Navy or the Marine Corps, but nearly all of them went in there, went to Leon Springs.
And then when we got to Leon Springs, they would transfer them into the artillery or
into the cavalry or into the infantry.
What branch did you serve in?
I served in artillery.
Where all did you serve?
Just in the States.
Just in the States.
I was sent to Camp Taylor, an artillery school.
Which is where?
It's now Camp Knox, Louisville, Kentucky.
Louisville, Kentucky.
And what you primarily were involved in then?
I did not get overseas.
You were training new inductees?
That's right.
Okay, and you were released in what, 1919?
Yeah, December 1919.
And then what did you do?
I went back home and went farming.
What kind of farming did you do?
Cotton farming, cattle.
I did it pretty hard, the cattle.
When I got out of service, cotton was 40 cents a pound.
It went to 12 cents a pound.
The cows were $70 a head, and they went to $20 a head.
So I started out.
So how long did you remain in the farming business?
1927, when I moved to Amarillo.
What led you to come to Amarillo?
Well, Amarillo was a booming town then.
It struck all around you.
I moved out of the house I was born in when I moved to Amarillo.
Two oldest children were born in St. Louis, but I was going to get away then.
So you just kind of pulled up stakes from Caldwell and came west then?
Came west, that's right.
Did you move by automobile or did you have some other means of transportation?
Well, it came in a model train.
Model train.
Wife and children came on the train.
I came ahead of them.
Did you have a prospect of a job here before you decided to move?
No, I wasn't.
Just opened up a little material business.
Is that what then became the, ultimately, what?
James Brick and Supply Company, which now be run by my son, Al, who's class 42.
And then we also had a business in Lubbock, Western Brick and Supply Company.
And I was interested in organizing, saving them, or saving the loan.
Could you tell us a little bit about the business that you started?
It was the supply company primarily of bricks and tiles.
That's right.
We went into other building materials.
Well, did you... Steel windows, steel doors.
Where did you get your brick?
Did you have a plan for making them?
No, there's no bricks been made in the pan.
They're shipped from East Texas, or Mineral Wells, Texas, or Brownwood, Texas.

all that brick that comes in here shipped in here they haven't found a suitable material here to make them so you you uh brought them in and sold them to contractors who were contractors and then you when did when did you uh sell your
your company to your son?
